<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-249-360  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 249 360.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 8 1989 v6 n18 p70(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Businessland to resell NeXT workstations in volume starting inJuly.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cortino, Juli.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Businessland Inc. (marketing)NeXT Inc. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    BLI.andO;Product:   Next (Workstation) (marketing).andO;Topic:     WorkstationsMarketingOutlookDealers and Agents.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Juli CortinoandM;SAN JOSE, Calif.andP;  -- Businessland Inc. will put the NeXT Inc. workstation onthe shelves of 91 retail outlets within two weeks, said NeXT President StevenJobs at a marketing road show last week for his newest machine.andM;Businessland President David Norman said the retail chain, based here, willstock the NeXT computer in volume beginning in July, when the final versionof the machine's operating system is due to be released.andM;Under a recent agreement with the Palo Alto, Calif., computer maker,Businessland will resell $150 million worth of NeXT systems over the next 12months at a base price of $9,995.andM;The NeXT machine is the first to be sold through a new Businessland unit,called the Advanced Systems Division.andP;  The division, headed by Kevin Compton,vice president, was established solely to handle Unix-related sales.andP;  Thedivision will work with NeXT to tie its machine into IBM and DigitalEquipment Corp. host environments, said Compton.andM;Businessland spokeswoman Suzanne Crocker said the chain chose to carry theNeXT machine over Sun Microsystems Inc.'s SPARCstation 1.andP;  ''We had to make achoice between two Unix-based systems, and we chose NeXT,'' she said.andM;NeXT is working with Dow Jones andamp; Co. to store the Wall Street Journal in theNeXT system's digital library, Jobs said.andP;  The database of articles can thenbe searched by entering a key word into the system.andM;Jobs also said Pittsburgh's Carnegie-Mellon University is in the process ofporting sound- and speech-recognition technology to the NeXT machine, andthat the digital sound processor will be rolled out later this year.andM;Lotus Development Corp. is porting its ''next generation of analyticalsoftware'' to the NeXT machine, Jobs said.andP;  Other software being portedincludes Adobe Systems Inc.'s Illustrator, Aldus Corp.'s PageMaker, FrameTechnology Corp.'s FrameMaker, Sybase Inc.'s SQL Server and Novell Inc.'sPortable NetWare.andO;</TEXT></DOC>